max, min, sum, median, standard deviation¶

monthly_climatology_max = ds.groupby('time.month').max(dim='time')

monthly_climatology_min = ds.groupby('time.month').min(dim='time')

monthly_climatology_sum = ds.groupby('time.month').sum(dim='time')

monthly_climatology_median = ds.groupby('time.month').median(dim='time')

monthly_climatology_stdev = ds.groupby('time.month').std(dim='time')

Plot Monthly Climatology¶

In [11]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))

plt.rcParams['axes.titlesize'] =12
plt.rcParams['axes.titlepad'] =10

plt.subplots_adjust(left=0.1, bottom=0.1, right=0.9, top=0.9, wspace=0.1, hspace=0.5)

plt.suptitle("Monthly Climatology",  fontsize=24)

lon2d, lat2d = np.meshgrid(monthly_climatology.longitude,monthly_climatology.latitude)  

extent = [33, 48, 3, 15]
central_lon, central_lat = 37,7

ax1 = plt.subplot(4,3,1, projection=ccrs.PlateCarree(central_longitude=central_lon, globe=None))
ct1 = ax1.pcolormesh(lon2d, lat2d, monthly_climatology.t2m[0,:,:], 
                     transform=ccrs.PlateCarree(), cmap='summer')
ax1.add_feature(cfeature.OCEAN, zorder=100, edgecolor='k', facecolor='blue')
ax1.add_feature(cfeature.BORDERS, edgecolor='black')
ax1.add_feature(cfeature.LAKES, edgecolor='black')
ax1.coastlines(resolution='10m')
ax1.set_extent(extent)
ax1.gridlines()
ax1.set_xticks(np.arange(33,49,3), crs=ccrs.PlateCarree())
ax1.set_yticks(np.arange(3,16,3), crs=ccrs.PlateCarree())

lon_formatter = LongitudeFormatter(zero_direction_label=True)
lat_formatter = LatitudeFormatter()
ax1.xaxis.set_major_formatter(lon_formatter)
ax1.yaxis.set_major_formatter(lat_formatter)
cb = plt.colorbar(ct1 ,orientation="vertical",extendrect='True', shrink = 0.5)
ax1.set(title="Month 1")
        
ax2 = plt.subplot(4,3,2, projection=ccrs.PlateCarree(central_longitude=central_lon, globe=None))
ct2 = ax2.pcolormesh(lon2d, lat2d, monthly_climatology.t2m[1,:,:],
                     transform=ccrs.PlateCarree(), cmap='summer')
ax2.add_feature(cfeature.OCEAN, zorder=100, edgecolor='k', facecolor='blue')
ax2.add_feature(cfeature.BORDERS, edgecolor='black')
ax2.add_feature(cfeature.LAKES, edgecolor='black')
ax2.coastlines(resolution='10m')
ax2.set_extent(extent)

extent = [33, 48, 3, 15]
central_lon, central_lat = 37,7

ax1 = plt.subplot(1,3,1, projection=ccrs.PlateCarree(central_longitude=central_lon, globe=None))
ct1 = ax1.pcolormesh(lon2d, lat2d, seasonal_climatology.t2m[0,:,:], 
                     transform=ccrs.PlateCarree(), cmap='summer')

ax1.add_feature(cfeature.BORDERS, edgecolor='black')
ax1.add_feature(cfeature.LAKES, edgecolor='black')
ax1.coastlines(resolution='10m')
ax1.set_extent(extent)
ax1.gridlines()
ax1.set_xticks(np.arange(33,49,3), crs=ccrs.PlateCarree())
ax1.set_yticks(np.arange(3,16,3), crs=ccrs.PlateCarree())

lon_formatter = LongitudeFormatter(zero_direction_label=True)
lat_formatter = LatitudeFormatter()
ax1.xaxis.set_major_formatter(lon_formatter)
ax1.yaxis.set_major_formatter(lat_formatter)
cb = plt.colorbar(ct1 ,orientation="vertical",extendrect='True', shrink = 0.15)
ax1.set(title="JJAS")

Work on Irregular Grids¶

  • a contour plot of my irregularly spaced data.

  • first you interpolate it to a regular grid.

  • As of version 0.98.3, matplotlib provides a griddata function that behaves similarly to the matlab version.

  • It performs "natural neighbor interpolation" of irregularly spaced data a regular grid, which you can then plot with contour, imshow or pcolor.

In [46]:
# make up some randomly distributed data
seed(1234)

npts = 200

x = uniform(-2,2,npts)
y = uniform(-2,2,npts)

z = x*np.exp(-x**2-y**2)

# define grid.
xi = np.linspace(-2.1,2.1,100)
yi = np.linspace(-2.1,2.1,100)

# grid the data.
zi = griddata((x, y), z, (xi[None,:], yi[:,None]), method='cubic')

# contour the gridded data, plotting dots at the randomly spaced data points.
CS = plt.contour(xi,yi,zi,15,linewidths=0.5,colors='k')
CS = plt.contourf(xi,yi,zi,15,cmap=plt.cm.jet)

plt.colorbar() # draw colorbar
# plot data points.

plt.scatter(x,y,marker='o',c='b',s=5)

plt.xlim(-2,2)
plt.ylim(-2,2)

plt.title('griddata test (%d points)' % npts)
Out[46]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'griddata test (200 points)')
